WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:27.960
<v John>The movement from self-certainty to perception, you know, it's like, I get it.</v>

00:00:27.960 --> 00:00:37.140
<v John>I mean, it makes sense. I understand. I mean, for me, I had a number of thoughts and notes that I jotted down, not least of which is nobody talks very much.</v>

00:00:37.180 --> 00:00:52.020
<v John>There must have been like a huge mine filled with semicolons somewhere in the Jena region because this book, the number of semicolons per page is like nothing I've ever seen.</v>

00:00:52.920 --> 00:01:07.260
<v Nate>Yeah. No, the syntax is so strange. And I don't bizarre. It's not it's not secondary. I mean, that's something I think I will continuously come back to is kind of part of my thesis on Hegel.</v>

00:01:07.260 --> 00:01:14.480
<v Nate>Like the syntax is what gives the dialectic its life. Like it's not some accessory to the text.</v>

00:01:15.160 --> 00:01:26.500
<v John>So you should read Dan Smith, who used to be here. He's now well, he's out of academia now down in Texas. He wrote, I think, an excellent piece. It's called like bad writing.</v>

00:01:27.380 --> 00:01:39.060
<v John>If you text me, you know, I'll forget. But if you text or email me, I'll remember and find the site for you. But his claim there is that the movement of Hegel, he uses Hegel, Adorno, and I think Zizek.</v>

00:01:39.680 --> 00:01:47.880
<v John>And he's like, it's negative dialectic, whatever. But the claim is precisely what you're saying, which is the syntax is the pedagogy.</v>

00:01:48.420 --> 00:01:48.600
<v John>Right.</v>

00:01:48.680 --> 00:01:53.860
<v John>You know, so it's just a site that you can use. And it's a smart article. It's Dan. He's a smart guy.</v>

00:01:54.300 --> 00:01:57.200
<v Nate>Yeah. No, I'll have to. I'll write it down. Dan Smith.</v>

00:01:57.320 --> 00:01:57.480
<v Nate>Yeah.</v>

00:01:57.580 --> 00:02:16.740
<v John>Yeah. Dan Smith. And the title of it is like bad writing. He's taking people that have conventionally been considered bad writers. And he's saying it's only bad writing in the sense of some romantic experience of reading. It's not bad writing in the sense of a pedagogy.</v>

00:02:17.140 --> 00:02:17.260
<v John>Right.</v>

00:02:17.260 --> 00:02:19.400
<v John>And that those are different kinds of things, you know.</v>

00:02:19.920 --> 00:02:27.780
<v John>So, yeah, it's Hegel, Adorno. And I really feel like the third is Zizek, the third example he takes, but I'm not sure.</v>

00:02:28.620 --> 00:02:31.120
<v John>Could it be Butler with the bad writing awards?</v>

00:02:31.900 --> 00:02:34.900
<v John>It could have been Butler. You might be right. It could have been.</v>

00:02:35.200 --> 00:02:37.460
<v John>Yeah, she's always talked about with that conversation.</v>

00:02:38.360 --> 00:02:41.840
<v John>Yeah, but that's a different, I mean, that circumstance was so political.</v>

00:02:42.820 --> 00:02:42.980
<v John>Yeah.</v>

00:02:43.640 --> 00:02:49.660
<v John>I mean, implicitly. So a lot of people don't. Like Chris Holcomb wrote and published an essay on this and never really knew.</v>

00:02:49.920 --> 00:02:55.620
<v John>Because when he showed it to me and I was like, Chris, you completely ignore the politics of this journal.</v>

00:02:55.780 --> 00:03:00.720
<v John>Like it's a journal that gave her that award and it's an analytic, it's a conservative analytic journal.</v>

00:03:01.540 --> 00:03:05.360
<v John>And if you look at the winners, they're all continental, you know, continental philosophers.</v>

00:03:05.820 --> 00:03:11.500
<v Nate>Well, it's funny to me, like reading this and then going to Butler and being like, she's too confusing.</v>

00:03:12.160 --> 00:03:22.920
<v Nate>Like, yeah, but Butler is like, like very clear and like there's an emphasis on clarity and simplicity when you look at someone like Hegel or someone like Deleuze.</v>

00:03:23.020 --> 00:03:27.620
<v Nate>Like, you know what I mean? Like what? I've never had the sensation that Butler was difficult to read.</v>

00:03:28.420 --> 00:03:28.520
<v John>Yeah.</v>

00:03:28.640 --> 00:03:28.960
<v John>Me neither.</v>

00:03:29.340 --> 00:03:29.540
<v Nate>Agree.</v>

00:03:30.020 --> 00:03:30.580
<v John>Yeah.</v>

00:03:30.940 --> 00:03:31.580
<v Nathaniel>Agree with you.</v>

00:03:31.800 --> 00:03:36.740
<v Nathaniel>I mean, not in any way, not in any sense that any philosophy is difficult to read.</v>

00:03:36.980 --> 00:03:37.220
<v Nathaniel>Right.</v>

00:03:37.560 --> 00:03:38.200
<v Nathaniel>Right, right, right.</v>

00:03:39.100 --> 00:03:39.320
<v John>Right.</v>

00:03:39.660 --> 00:03:45.460
<v John>And unfortunately, but unfortunately she wrote that, the same has been true whenever I teach that in grad classes.</v>

00:03:46.040 --> 00:03:49.680
<v John>Grad students across the board are always like, why do people think this is so hard to read?</v>

00:03:49.780 --> 00:03:52.100
<v John>Like, this doesn't seem that hard to read.</v>

00:03:52.180 --> 00:03:53.820
<v John>I mean, it's philosophy, you know.</v>

00:03:54.220 --> 00:04:00.600
<v John>But unfortunately she wrote that, she wrote a defense after, this is a couple years after, after getting that award.</v>

00:04:00.680 --> 00:04:07.980
<v John>She wrote a defense that was published in the New York Times and her defense was difficult ideas require difficult writing, which is the worst.</v>

00:04:08.940 --> 00:04:10.600
<v John>I mean, to me, it's the worst defense.</v>

00:04:10.780 --> 00:04:15.100
<v John>Like, the proper defense is this is not difficult writing for people who read philosophy.</v>

00:04:15.760 --> 00:04:16.520
<v Nate>Right, yeah.</v>

00:04:16.600 --> 00:04:17.880
<v Nate>She should have just done that take.</v>

00:04:17.880 --> 00:04:19.560
<v Nate>Yeah, that would have been a more modest take.</v>

00:04:20.360 --> 00:04:21.040
<v Nate>Right, right.</v>

00:04:21.160 --> 00:04:33.020
<v John>Well, because what she does is she links the ideas to the quality of the writing and that's a whole representational argument that shouldn't, she shouldn't, you wouldn't think that she would be supportive.</v>

00:04:33.640 --> 00:04:34.340
<v John>That's right.</v>

00:04:34.960 --> 00:04:41.620
<v John>I regret, I mean, it's so much because so many times I've heard people reference Butler's defense and I'm like, oh, I hate that defense so much.</v>

00:04:41.920 --> 00:04:49.440
<v John>There's a really good one, which is, this is a specialist idiom like every other specialist idiom in the world.</v>

00:04:50.100 --> 00:04:50.140
<v John>Right.</v>

00:04:50.320 --> 00:04:56.160
<v John>And for that specialist idiom, it's not to, like, mathematics is bad writing, right?</v>

00:04:56.560 --> 00:04:58.960
<v John>Because it's not written for us to understand.</v>

00:04:59.100 --> 00:05:01.000
<v John>Like, quantum mechanics, bad writing.</v>

00:05:01.240 --> 00:05:01.440
<v John>Yeah.</v>

00:05:01.540 --> 00:05:09.060
<v John>Nobody says quantum mechanics is bad writing because they understand it's a specialist language, an idiom for physicists.</v>

00:05:10.180 --> 00:05:16.200
<v Nate>Yeah, it's a technical language and insofar as Butler's is a technical language, it's pretty simple.</v>

00:05:16.640 --> 00:05:27.460
<v Nate>It's symmetrical, it's not, like, it's not even that ambiguous when you, like, if you compare it to Hegel or a lot of these writers that we're, that we're dealing with, you know?</v>

00:05:27.780 --> 00:05:28.040
<v John>Yeah.</v>

00:05:29.280 --> 00:05:29.680
<v John>Yeah.</v>

00:05:29.820 --> 00:05:35.400
<v John>Although, interestingly, people don't really say that about Deleuze, even though Deleuze is way harder to read.</v>

00:05:35.860 --> 00:05:48.140
<v John>But because it's so clearly making, you know, neologism, you know, because it's so clearly kind of playful, for whatever reason, people just don't associate that with bad writing.</v>

00:05:48.260 --> 00:05:53.800
<v John>And they just, like, oh, well, they're being playful, they're just making up bodybuildings and, right, they're creative, right, right.</v>

00:05:54.140 --> 00:05:54.260
<v Nate>Yeah.</v>

00:05:55.120 --> 00:06:05.840
<v Nate>But I have a strain, I mean, I'm still, my reading and relationship with Butler has sort of evolved over the last few years and she's still pretty central to my project.</v>

00:06:06.340 --> 00:06:15.920
<v Nate>But if you read any of, like, her most recent stuff, it seems like she's kind of regressed into just a basic liberal humanism.</v>

00:06:16.420 --> 00:06:27.360
<v Nate>Like, and I know there's, there's a difference between pop Butler and, like, hard theoretical Butler, but the pop Butler is not good for me.</v>

00:06:27.780 --> 00:06:37.180
<v Nate>Like, she's published a couple pieces in just, like, popular magazines recently and it's like, these are just strange, like, really conservative arguments, you know?</v>

00:06:37.280 --> 00:06:37.500
<v Nate>Yeah.</v>

00:06:37.580 --> 00:06:38.780
<v Nate>I don't know if you've read any of them.</v>

00:06:38.980 --> 00:06:40.080
<v John>It's hard to imagine.</v>

00:06:40.160 --> 00:06:40.800
<v John>I have.</v>

00:06:41.140 --> 00:06:42.860
<v John>I've had the same response that you did.</v>

00:06:42.960 --> 00:06:45.080
<v John>It's like, this sounds like liberalism to me.</v>

00:06:45.360 --> 00:06:45.520
<v John>Yeah.</v>

00:06:45.520 --> 00:06:50.040
<v John>The only thing that I give her a break for, well, there are many things I give her a break for because I think she's smart as fuck.</v>

00:06:50.240 --> 00:06:57.080
<v John>But, like, being in a position like she is is something that I will never understand, which is I have to write, right?</v>

00:06:57.120 --> 00:06:59.500
<v John>I get to write for you guys, right?</v>

00:06:59.560 --> 00:07:06.520
<v John>And for a fairly narrow group of, you know, of sort of theory types in the rhetoric field or whatever.</v>

00:07:06.660 --> 00:07:09.300
<v John>And maybe there's a few outliers in philosophy or whatever.</v>

00:07:09.300 --> 00:07:18.780
<v John>But, like, I don't ever have to be concerned that the bulk of the people responding to my thing are going to say, make it intelligible to me, you know?</v>

00:07:18.960 --> 00:07:19.140
<v John>Right.</v>

00:07:19.220 --> 00:07:20.220
<v John>And she really is.</v>

00:07:20.280 --> 00:07:25.900
<v John>I mean, she is a – she's more of a public figure than sort of intellectual anymore.</v>

00:07:26.020 --> 00:07:27.820
<v John>And I don't mean that as a disparaging comment.</v>

00:07:27.960 --> 00:07:39.800
<v John>It's because of her extraordinary success that she's called on and asked to speak to, you know, the Palestinian question at MLA, for example, a couple of years ago, right, when there was that.</v>

00:07:40.220 --> 00:07:43.580
<v John>And she is called upon to offer a perspective.</v>

00:07:43.820 --> 00:07:57.740
<v John>Well, you know, she can't possibly be a master of all of this content and also speak to all of these constituencies in that sort of – you know, Derrida, you know, there's Derrida that's like that as well.</v>

00:07:57.740 --> 00:08:06.940
<v John>You know, there are times where, like, talking on apartheid and he usually managed to turn it back to some sort of esoteric question of hospitality and et cetera, et cetera.</v>

00:08:07.120 --> 00:08:17.240
<v John>But there are moments where I'm like, yeah, I just can't understand the position that a person like that has gone from this and now they've got a – we call it a larger public.</v>

00:08:17.360 --> 00:08:19.900
<v John>But it's just a different – it's a different public.</v>

00:08:20.920 --> 00:08:23.740
<v John>And to write, it's like I don't –</v>

00:08:23.740 --> 00:08:31.620
<v Nate>Yeah, well, you assume a political position and then your views sort of by necessity have to be narrowed in a way, you know.</v>

00:08:31.620 --> 00:08:42.040
<v Nate>I mean, her defense of academia in that one article – I forget what the publication was – it was like this makes perfect sense if you're speaking from her position.</v>

00:08:42.840 --> 00:08:43.500
<v Nate>Right, right.</v>

00:08:43.500 --> 00:08:52.880
<v Nate>So, but from anybody – from my position, from your guys' position, it's like that argument, it was so elitist, which whatever, there's good and bad versions of every writer.</v>

00:08:53.380 --> 00:08:56.000
<v Nate>So, it's like, well, I guess this is just the version I don't like.</v>

00:08:56.420 --> 00:08:57.120
