<v Nate>Yeah.</v>

00:09:01.840 --> 00:09:02.400
<v John>But, yeah.</v>

00:09:02.540 --> 00:09:16.260
<v John>And she—and I think—I mean, look, the other thing to keep in mind is how totally excoriated she was by so many feminists back in the 80s—well, rather, the 90s, late 80s and early 90s because of her stuff was unreadable.</v>

00:09:16.260 --> 00:09:18.920
<v John>And that she was not supporting the cause.</v>

00:09:18.920 --> 00:09:21.500
<v John>And my take on that was that bothered her, right?</v>

00:09:21.640 --> 00:09:27.240
<v John>Like, because she very much saw herself as an activist, activist theorist.</v>

00:09:28.220 --> 00:09:38.240
<v John>And so, yeah, it does seem like her work became more recognizably activist rather than recognizably—I mean, she's still smart as fuck, like, obviously.</v>

00:09:38.720 --> 00:09:45.500
<v John>But it just seems—and, again, that's a circumstance where I can't imagine it, you know?</v>

00:09:45.980 --> 00:09:47.820
<v Nathaniel>I think that—that's my sense, too.</v>

00:09:47.940 --> 00:09:59.960
<v Nathaniel>I mean, think about the sort of genealogy and series of critiques she gives at the beginning of Gender Trouble where, I mean, it's not just that, you know, she's got shit for being, you know, quote, unquote, unreadable.</v>

00:09:59.960 --> 00:10:09.000
<v Nathaniel>But she also, like, really went after a whole bunch of, you know, concepts that are pretty central to most versions of feminism.</v>

00:10:09.400 --> 00:10:13.820
<v Nathaniel>Like, there is a recognizable thing that we can call woman, right?</v>

00:10:14.040 --> 00:10:14.360
<v John>Right.</v>

00:10:14.780 --> 00:10:24.060
<v Nathaniel>Which, to me, I mean, that makes Butler far more interesting as a—I mean, as a feminist to actually take up, you know, woman—the category of woman as a question.</v>

00:10:24.060 --> 00:10:37.060
<v Nathaniel>And to question the—I mean, to my mind, you know, like, her and de Beauvoir are, you know, at the—you know, are the most interesting thinkers in that arena.</v>

00:10:37.220 --> 00:10:55.920
<v Nathaniel>But someone like Siksou, who just sort of, like, assumes sort of, like, prefigured versions of masculinity and femininity and then ascribes them to kinds of writing, is just like, you know, you're not actually thinking about gender.</v>

00:10:56.060 --> 00:11:03.060
<v Nathaniel>You're just thinking about the way that contemporary gender norms get distributed and pointing out very obvious disparities between them.</v>

00:11:03.100 --> 00:11:04.680
<v Nathaniel>But you're not thinking about gender at all.</v>

00:11:04.680 --> 00:11:09.420
<v John>I mean, that's a—that's the tough part.</v>

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:10.200
<v Nate>Yeah.</v>

00:11:10.420 --> 00:11:24.440
<v Nate>What seems to suck is that, like, the more activist, like, the bent of your writing becomes or the more—like, if you have dogs in a fight, the less adventurous and provocative your thinking becomes.</v>

00:11:24.700 --> 00:11:27.120
<v Nate>Which doesn't seem like it has to be the case.</v>

00:11:27.160 --> 00:11:30.200
<v Nate>It just seems like that's usually the way it goes, you know.</v>

00:11:30.560 --> 00:11:46.360
<v Nate>Which it's like someone like Zizek, he will have, like, kind of activist political tendencies, but the writing itself doesn't seem to be burdened by, like, a responsibility to humanity or to a specific group, you know.</v>

00:11:46.360 --> 00:12:01.480
<v Nate>Which I find that uncomfortable sometimes reading him, but I also—I don't think I could ever, like, fully just endorse something, which is what Butler seems to lean into later in her career, you know, that kind of orientation.</v>

00:12:01.900 --> 00:12:02.380
<v Nate>I don't know.</v>

00:12:02.660 --> 00:12:13.500
<v Nate>I mean, it seems like you could find a balance between those two, but for me, the more explicitly, like, about social justice issues you become, the less adventurous the thinking.</v>

00:12:14.040 --> 00:12:14.700
<v Nate>I don't know.</v>

00:12:14.800 --> 00:12:15.480
<v Nate>It's just—yeah.</v>

00:12:16.360 --> 00:12:23.320
<v Nathaniel>Well, you have to harden yourself into a position to advocate for something generally means you have to articulate the boundaries of the thing that you're advocating for, right?</v>

00:12:23.440 --> 00:12:23.640
<v Nathaniel>Right.</v>

00:12:23.880 --> 00:12:24.240
<v Nathaniel>Yeah, exactly.</v>

00:12:24.760 --> 00:12:39.000
<v John>And I've always felt like—and this is just in the microcosm that is the classroom, but particularly for undergrads, but I've always felt like current events, like, I felt a responsibility to say something interesting about them.</v>

00:12:39.160 --> 00:12:47.740
<v John>And I often don't have anything interesting to say, and I feel like that, like—and that's a much, much smaller microcosm.</v>

00:12:47.740 --> 00:13:00.280
<v John>I imagine, you know, projecting that to the position of, like, you know, Judith Butler or Zizek or someone who, you know, where anything that they write on a topic—and they're being asked constantly, like, hey, will you write about this issue?</v>

00:13:00.360 --> 00:13:02.100
<v John>Will you write about—will you do something on this issue?</v>

00:13:02.220 --> 00:13:05.760
